 2751929, "title": "Rock U.S.A. Part 2", "work_id": 98056, "role": "producer/director", "role_id": 31, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2751927, "title": "Rock U.S.A. Part 1", "work_id": 98055, "role": "producer/director", "role_id": 31, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "07 JUL 1942", "date_of_death": "22 JUL 1992", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 1, "name": "English", "slug": "english"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 1, "name": "United States of America", "slug": "united-states-of-america"}], "biography": "Christian Blackwood (July 7, 1942 – July 22, 1992) was an American film director and cinematographer.He was initially a child actor, then a cinematographer acclaimed for his work in Charlotte Zwerin's Thelonious Monk: Straight, No Chaser. But his major work was as the director of over 80 films, mostly documentaries, over a 25-year career. His most famous films are Observations Under The Volcano and On the Set of Death of a Salesman, behind-the-scenes looks at the creation of movies by John Huston and Volker Schlöndorff from the famous novel and play. The latter film won him the grand prize at the Sundance Film Festival.\n\nChristian Blackwood died in 1992 of lung cancer. He was married to film writer, producer and fine art photographer, Carolyn Marks Blackwood. His brother was Michael Blackwood. His film archives are stored in the Museum of Modern Art. Source: Wikidata; 01/08/2023", "biography_author": null, "date_of_biography": "2025-03-13T00:55:15.625462+11:00", "external_links": [{"id": 3761, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Blackwood"}], "uuid": "ec2cda12-a65e-4451-bf8b-9c8c31f98c20", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "1549", "external_references": [{"id": 24934, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q5109340"}, {"id": 27822, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "1543707"}, {"id": 27823, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "n87927314"}, {"id": 27824, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-n87927314"}], "date_modified": "2025-03-13T00:55:15.625777+11:00"}, {"id": 76133, "name": "George Nierenberg", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2164279, "title": "No maps on my taps", "work_id": 77927, "role": "producer/director", "role_id": 31, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "", "date_of_death": "", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [], "places_of_operation": [], "biography": "George T. Nierenberg is a New York-based documentary filmmaker and creator of GTN Creative.\nHis 1975 film The Hollow is a documentary about a family in the Adirondacks.His 1979 Emmy award winning film \"No Maps on My Taps\" explored American tap dance and has been credited as bringing about a revival to the form. Following the success of the film, famous featured tap dancers began the \"No Maps on My Taps and Company\" tour around the world, performing at over 60 locations. Again documenting the culture around tap dance, Nierenberg made \"About Tap\", featuring Gregory Hines and stylistic performances and recollections by three of America’s leading male tap dancers: Steve Condos, Jimmy Slyde and Chuck Green. For his contribution to the form, Nierenberg was awarded in 2014 the American Tap Dance Foundation's Tap Preservation Award, given to an outstanding individual or organization in the field for the superior advancement of tap dance through presentation and preservation.His 1982 film Say Amen Somebody! documents gospel music and New York Magazine placed it at number 31 on their list of the 50 Best Documentaries of All Time in 2019. In \"That Rhythm, Those Blues\" (1988), Nierenberg celebrated R&B and laid bare the racism in the music industry of the 1950s, for which Nierenberg was nominated for a Best Director Emmy. Milestone Films restored and re-released \"Say Amen, Somebody\" and \"No Maps on My Taps\" theatrically to acclaim in 2017.Working in television, Nierenberg produced, directed and developed projects for PBS, AMC, Bravo, Nickelodeon, and Sony BMG, including: Neon Lights, for National Geographic’s Explorer and a film on Voodoo in Haiti for ABC’s Day One. In 1983, Nierenberg made \"Moment of Crisis\" about the JFK assassination for NBC.  Nierenberg was enlisted as a producer to launch Saturday Night with Connie Chung on CBS.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-08-01T14:58:54.395700+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 2121, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Nierenberg"}], "uuid": "36ad6c2e-c60f-402a-be91-f1fd13b037a6", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "19651", "external_references": [{"id": 9138, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q104866836"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-05T20:06:11.078399+10:00"}, {"id": 76132, "name": "Alison Head", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2379684, "title": "Understanding is not enough", "work_id": 77926, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "", "date_of_death": "", "genders": [], "languages": [], "places_of_operation": [], "biography": "", "biography_author": null, "date_of_biography": "2023-07-19T03:36:16.341958+10:00", "external_links": [], "uuid": "72613d7b-e9dd-4501-9b86-6c93eb184f44", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "4173", "external_references": [{"id": 37040, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q121299305"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-05T17:28:53.049110+10:00"}, {"id": 76131, "name": "Keith Head", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2379683, "title": "Understanding is not enough", "work_id": 77926, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 767895, "title": "The Span project", "work_id": 78724, "role": "producer/director